{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"872b2123-ddb3-4723-be07-bdf5a8899ece","content":"In .NET MAUI, you configure platform lifecycle events in your `MauiProgram.cs` using `ConfigureLifecycleEvents`:\n\n```csharp\nusing Microsoft.Maui.LifecycleEvents;\n\npublic static MauiApp CreateMauiApp()\n{\n    var builder = MauiApp.CreateBuilder();\n    builder.UseMauiApp<App>();\n\n    builder.ConfigureLifecycleEvents(events =>\n    {\n#if ANDROID\n        events.AddAndroid(android => android\n            .OnPause(activity => { /* your code */ })\n            .OnStop(activity => { /* your code */ }));\n#elif IOS\n        events.AddiOS(ios => ios\n            .DidEnterBackground(app => { /* your code */ }));\n#endif\n    });\n\n    return builder.Build();\n}\n```\n\n**Key points:**\n- Add `using Microsoft.Maui.LifecycleEvents;`\n- Use `#if ANDROID` / `#elif IOS` preprocessor directives to keep platform code conditional\n- Android exposes `OnPause`, `OnStop`, `OnResume`, `OnDestroy`, etc.\n- iOS exposes `DidEnterBackground`, `WillEnterForeground`, `WillTerminate`, etc.\n- Each callback receives the native platform object (`Activity` on Android, `UIApplication` on iOS)","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"8e08fc69-78d2-4a7b-a244-ee1743f3dfef","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about how to hook into platform-specific lifecycle events in .NET MAUI. This is a general knowledge question about .NET MAUI development. I can answer this directly without needing to search any codebase.","outputTokens":399,"requestId":"F3D1:13D2B1:1E27A3D:21F8E5B:69E819FE"},"id":"0b6791b1-3733-4ebb-a046-239244084ea9","timestamp":"2026-04-22T00:44:54.154Z","parentId":"fe269ba8-efed-475f-89b8-5df290a6df21"}
